---

## Summary

| # | Severity | Issue | OWASP |
|---|----------|-------|-------|
| 1 | Medium | No security headers (Helmet missing) | A05: Security Misconfiguration |
| 2 | Medium | PII (email addresses) returned on unauthenticated endpoint | A01: Broken Access Control / A04: Insecure Design |
| 3 | Medium | No authentication / authorization on `/users` | A01: Broken Access Control / A07: Auth Failures |
| 4 | Medium | No rate limiting — exposed to brute force / DoS | A04: Insecure Design |
| 5 | Low | No CORS policy defined (default is permissive when proxied) | A05: Security Misconfiguration |
| 6 | Low | No request body size limits / no body parser hardening | A05: Security Misconfiguration |
| 7 | Low | No structured error-handling middleware — stack traces may leak | A09: Logging & Monitoring / A05 |
| 8 | Low | Binds to all interfaces (`app.listen(3000)`) with no TLS | A02: Cryptographic Failures |
| 9 | Info | `x-powered-by: Express` header leaks framework fingerprint | A05 |
| 10 | Info | Hardcoded user data — fine for a demo, but signals no DB-layer validation pattern exists yet | A03 (preventative) |

**Not present (good):** No SQL, no `eval`/`Function`, no shell exec, no user-controlled file paths, no template rendering, no deserialization, no regex on user input, no redirects. So classic injection (A03) isn't reachable **today** — but the app has no validation scaffolding, so the next endpoint added is where risk lands.

---

## Findings & Recommendations

### 1. Missing security headers — add Helmet
Express ships with zero security headers. Clickjacking, MIME sniffing, and XSS mitigations are all off.

```js
const helmet = require('helmet');
app.use(helmet()); // sets CSP, X-Frame-Options, X-Content-Type-Options, etc.
app.disable('x-powered-by'); // remove fingerprint (Helmet does this too)
```

### 2 & 3. `/users` exposes PII without auth
`email` is personal data. Returning it on an unauthenticated endpoint is a broken-access-control finding even with seeded data, because the shape of the API becomes the contract for future real data.

```js
const jwt = require('jsonwebtoken');

function requireAuth(req, res, next) {
  const header = req.get('authorization') || '';
  const token = header.startsWith('Bearer ') ? header.slice(7) : null;
  if (!token) return res.status(401).json({ error: 'unauthorized' });
  try {
    req.user = jwt.verify(token, process.env.JWT_SECRET); // secret from env, never hardcoded
    next();
  } catch {
    return res.status(401).json({ error: 'unauthorized' });
  }
}

app.get('/users', requireAuth, (req, res) => {
  // Only return fields the caller is entitled to
  res.json(users.map(u => ({ id: u.id, name: u.name })));
});
```

If email must be returned, gate it behind an authorization check (`req.user.role === 'admin'` or "user is requesting themselves").

### 4. No rate limiting
An unauthenticated endpoint with no rate limit is trivially abusable for enumeration and DoS.

```js
const rateLimit = require('express-rate-limit');
app.use(rateLimit({
  windowMs: 60_000,
  max: 100,             // tune per-route as needed
  standardHeaders: true,
  legacyHeaders: false,
}));
```

### 5. Explicit CORS policy
Even if you don't enable CORS, declare the posture so a future `app.use(cors())` with defaults doesn't happen by accident.

```js
