### 1. Missing security headers (Medium)

`res.json()` doesn't set `X-Content-Type-Options`, `Strict-Transport-Security`, `Content-Security-Policy`, etc. Add Helmet.

```js
const helmet = require('helmet');
app.disable('x-powered-by');           // fixes #7 too
app.use(helmet());
```

### 2. PII exposure without authZ (Medium)

`GET /users` returns email addresses to any anonymous caller. Even with fake seed data, this pattern trains the wrong habit and will leak real PII once wired to a DB.

```js
const requireAuth = (req, res, next) => {
  const token = req.get('authorization')?.replace(/^Bearer\s+/i, '');
  if (!token || !isValidToken(token)) return res.sendStatus(401);
  req.user = decodeToken(token);
  next();
};

app.get('/users', requireAuth, (req, res) => {
  // Also: only return fields the caller is allowed to see.
  res.json(users.map(({ id, name }) => ({ id, name })));
});
```

For real auth, prefer a vetted library (`jsonwebtoken` with asymmetric keys, or session middleware like `express-session` backed by Redis with `secure`, `httpOnly`, `sameSite: 'lax'` cookies).

